# Approach
-> The idea is to sort the array in decending order and then apply two pointers the first pointer will point to the first element of any partition and second pointer will traverse and find the last element of the partition 

-> The job of second pointer is find to the element whose difference with the element (first pointer is pointing) is greater than the value k, and when we find that element simply increase the value of partition variable (this variable is counting the number of partions we require) 

-> The answer of the query is value of partition variable + 1 (because we need to return number of subsequences or partition)

```
Given nums = [3,6,1,2,5], k = 2
             part = 0
->           nums = 6  5  3  2  1  // After Sorting in Descending order
                    |  |
                    i  j           // Pointers
    n[i]-n[j] = 1 < 2          //ignore and increment value of j


->            nums = 6  5  3  2  1
                     |     |
                     i     j
    n[i]-n[j] = 3 > 2   // increment partition variable's value by 1 and do i=j


-> Now,        nums = 6  5 | 3  2  1
                             |  |
                             i  j
    n[i]-n[j] = 1 < 2  // ignore and increment value of j


           nums = 6  5 | 3  2  1
                         |     |
                         i     j  
    n[i]-n[j] = 2 == 2 //ignore and increment value of j


 j == n.size() therefore terminate the loop 

```

