# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
The goal is to divide the array into partitions such that the maximum difference between elements in each partition is at most k. Sorting the array helps ensure smaller differences between adjacent elements. Using a sliding window approach, maintain a window where the difference between the maximum and minimum elements is at most k. When this condition is violated, increment the output counter, indicating a new partition. Slide the window by updating the start and end pointers. Continue until the end of the array. The output counter will give the minimum number of partitions required.
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Sort the array to facilitate smaller differences.
Initialize a sliding window with start and end pointers.
Extend the window as long as the difference between nums[end] and nums[start] is within k.
If the difference condition is violated, increment output and move start to end.
Continue sliding the window until the end of the array.
The output counter represents the minimum number of partitions needed.

# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(N*logN)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(N)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int partitionArray(vector<int>& nums, int k) {
        int output = 0;
        sort(nums.begin() , nums.end());

        // sliding window
        int start = 0;
        int end = 0;
        while(end < nums.size()){
            // we can extend this window
            if(nums[end] - nums[start] <= k){
                end++;
            }
            // we cannot extend this window as doing so will give us a subsequence with range greater than k
            else{
                output++;
                start = end;
            }
        }
        // don't miss the last output
        output++;

        return output;
    }
};
```

